White wine quality

Introduction

In this project i choose to work with white wine quality dataset. White wine is a wine whose color can be straw-yellow, yellow-green or yellow-gold.It is produced by the alcoholic fermentation of the non-coloured pulp of the grapes, which may have a skin of any color. It is very difficult to assess the quality of wine by reading label. Quality is assessed best by tasting. Quite often you wont be able to taste a wine before buying, but information is available on wine lables to help you decide, although you will need a certain amount of the knowledge about the contents of the wine in prior.

There are 4898 observation and 12 varaiables to denote the composition and quality of white wine. From 12 of the variable 11 of them are numeric datatype and an integer to denote the quality of wine.

alcohol

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    8.00    9.50   10.40   10.51   11.40   14.20

In normal most of the white wine can have a alcohol content ranging from 5%-15%. In this dataset the alcohol content ranging from 8% to 14.20% and 50% of the wines are below 10.40% alcohol content.

residual sugar

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   0.600   1.700   5.200   6.391   9.900  65.800

Residual sugars are the sugars that are not converted into alcohol during fermentation. Residual sugar in wines ranges from 0 to 220 grams per liter sugar depanding on the style. Here it ranges from 0.600 to 65.800 with half of the wines fall below 5.200 and 75% of the wines have less than 9.900 residual sugar. Less than 25% wines have residual sugar greater than 10.0.

From the 25% wines that are below 9.900 most of them fall in the range of 10-20. Only few wines have residual sugar greater than 20.

Taste Type

Based on the residual sugar content in the wine , wines are classified into three type.

## 
## bone_dry      dry  off-dry 
##      170     3535     1193

Most of the wines are dry type wine.There is no wide spread sugar content in our dataset.

volatile acidity

In US legal limit of the volatile acidity is 1.1g/L. When volatile acidity becomes higher it gives the smell and taste of vinegar to the wine.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.0800  0.2100  0.2600  0.2782  0.3200  1.1000

About 75% of the wine has volatile acidity less than .3200.There is a steady decrease in volatile acidity after 0.3.

fixed acidity

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   3.800   6.300   6.800   6.855   7.300  14.200

Most of the data falls between the range of 6.3 to 7.3

PH

winemakers uses pH as a way to measure the acidity of the wine.Low pH wines will taste tart or crisp while the high pH wine are more susceptible for bacterial growth.Most of the wine pH fall around 3 to 4. pH of 3.0 to 3.4 is suitable for white wines.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   2.720   3.090   3.180   3.188   3.280   3.820

Here most of the wines have the pH within the range of 3 to 3.4.There are very few wines below 3.6pH.

citric acid

citric acid is minor in grapes, added after fermentation to add flavours to wine 

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.0000  0.2700  0.3200  0.3342  0.3900  1.6600

Most of the wine has less than 0.5g/L .There are also some wines with 0 citric acid in their content. when wine have low acidity then citric acid is added to increase their flavours to them.

chlorides

chloride content in wine is due to the vineyard which is present near sea or the irrigation by the salt water. In most cases the limit is 60mg/L or 0.06g/L.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
## 0.00900 0.03600 0.04300 0.04577 0.05000 0.34600

More than 75% of the wines have chlorides less than 0.06. There are also some wines higher than 0.06 but their count is very low.

sulfur dioxide

sulphates are added to produce sulfur dioxide in wine so that it can prevent it from oxidation and spoilage.sulfur dioxide is present in wine as free SO2 and also bound to acetaldehyde.The sum gives the total sulfur dioxide in wine. Legal limit of SO2 is 350mg/L and the sweet wine is 400mg/L.

## summary of free sulfur dioxide
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    2.00   23.00   34.00   35.31   46.00  289.00
## summary of bound sulfur dioxide
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##     4.0    78.0   100.0   103.1   125.0   331.0
## summary of total sulfur dioxide
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##     9.0   108.0   134.0   138.4   167.0   440.0
## summary of sulphates
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.2200  0.4100  0.4700  0.4898  0.5500  1.0800

About 95% of the wine has the total sulfur dioxide that is well below the legal limit. Bound sulfur dioxide is high in number comparing to the free sulfur dioxide in wine. In other words the total sulfur dioxide contains more bound SO2 than free SO2.

density

Density of the wine is closer to the density of water.According to winemakers sweet wine has more density than dry wine.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.9871  0.9917  0.9937  0.9940  0.9961  1.0390

Most of the wine has density between 0.985 to 1.000. In that about 50% data falls in the range of 0.9917 to 0.9961

quality

Quality is the score between 0 and 10.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   3.000   5.000   6.000   5.878   6.000   9.000

There is a peak at wine. It means more number of the wine has the quality as 6. Count is dropping after the quality 6. There is only 25% of the wine has more than 6 as a quality.

univariate analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

It has 4898 observations with 12 variables. In that 11 variables are of numeric datatype and one is an interger.

What are the main features of your dataset?

Main feature of the dataset is quality. All the other variables in the dataset contributes to the quality oneway or another. Change in the one or more variable may change the quality of the wine. So it is the main feature of the dataset.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help your support your investigation into your feature of your dataset?

residual sugar,alcohol,fixed acidity,volatile acidity and citric acid contribute aroma,taste and acidity to the wine so this will be important features to influence the quality of the white wine.

Did you create any new variables in the dataset?

Yes,I created two variables in the dataset. One is the taste_type. White wine bottles have labels to denote the sweetness.They are labeled based on the residual sugar content in the wine. So based on this i created a factor variable to denote the sweet type.

Another varaibel is bound.sulfur.dioxide. When sulphates are added it provide sulfur dioxide to the wine which inturn helps to fight againts the microbial spoilage.

of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust or change the form of the data? If so,why did you do this?

yes, density has the most unsual distribution.In density most of the wines fall in the short range that leads to more wines fall in the same bin. So i have to set the binwidth, limits and the breaks on the x axis to see how it is distributed.

Bivariate plot section.

fixed.acidity by pH

pH is the measure of the acidity of the solution. Higher the pH it contains less acid and vice versa.

## [1] -0.4258583

This show that pH and fixed acidity are negatively correlated.This prove the concept of measuring pH.They are correlated by -0.426.

chlorides vs quality

Reason i choose to explore quality vs chloride is When the chloride content becomes higher in the wine, it can affects the aroma of wine which in turn may affects the quality.

## [1] -0.2099344

In graph i use vertical line to denote the chlorides legal limit 0.06mg/L. In this plot for the higher quality there is not much wines beyond the legal limit. It shows that wine with high content of the chlorides dont have high quality and they have negative correlation which proves the point.But the strength of correlation is -0.21 that is not enough it affects the quality of the wine.

alcohol vs residual.sugar

During fermentation, sugars present in the wine are converted into alcohol.

## [1] -0.4506312

alcohol and the residual sugars are negatively correlated. This show that the higher the alcohol lesser the sugar content. There are correleted with -0.451.

quality vs alcohol

## [1] 0.4355747

Plot shows that quality and the alcohol are positively correlated with the correlation of 0.4355. There is a chance that wine with higheralcohol leads to high quality wine but correlation does not imply causation , there may be other factors that influence this correlation.

density vs alcohol

when calculating the density of the wine , the contents of the denisty of the wine are multiplied with their volume and added to give the wine density.

## [1] -0.7801376

Density and alcohol are negatively correlated with -0.781. It shows that when the alcohol content increases in wine the density of the wine tends to go down.

density vs residual sugar

## [1] 0.8389665

There is a strong correlation between residual sugar and the density. It is a positively correlated with 0.8389. It shows that when residual sugar content in wine increases then the density of the wine also increases.

Bivariate analysis

Talk about some of the relationship you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the features of interest vary with the other features in the dataset?

Quality is the important feature of the dataset. There is no interesting relationship for the quality in the dataset.When the chlorides increases it affects the wine quality as i assume but both are not strongly correlated to prove the assumption.When the alcohol content increases there is a increase in the quality but the strength is not high enough between them to take into] consideration.

Did you observe any intersting relationship with the other features?

Important relationship i found is the residual sugar with the alcohol and with the density. During the fermantation sugars are converted into the alcohol.As alcohol is the product of the sugar, it results in the negative correlation between them. In the case of calculating density , density of the contents are considerd. Sugar has the higher density than the alcohol. When the wine has high sugar content then it has a low alcohol content it automatically boost the density to high(sugar has higher density and sugar content high in wine). In other case when wine has high alcohol content then it has low sugar content which in turn makes the density of the wine to low.

What is the strongest realtionship you found?

The strongest relationship is between the residual sugars and the density. They are positively correlated with the strength of 0.8389.

Reflection

I explored nearly 5000 wines in this dataset.what suprised me is that none of variables are strongly related with the quality. There are some strong relation between density and sugar but these two are not correlated much with the quality. During the winemaking sugars are converted to alcohol, it is reflected in this dataset. And the chlorides content may change the quality of the wine, but there is not enough high quality wines to prove such a point.For residual sugars most of the wines have the low sugar content , thus it fail to show the relation with quality.For future investigation can add the variable like the date of the manufacturing of wine to see the ageing of wine has anything to do with the quality. wine with different chloride content and residual sugar content should be added in future. so that their influence on quality can be found.
